<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910124-0103</DOCNO><DOCID>910124-0103.</DOCID><HL>   Some Boeing Staffers Leave   Saudi Arabia, Others Stay</HL><DATE>01/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   BA MDEST</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   SEATTLE -- Boeing Co. said it flew an undisclosed numberof employees and 80 of their dependents out of Riyadh, SaudiArabia, where the company is to complete two militarycontracts for the Saudi government.   Despite the threat of Iraqi Scud missile attacks, anundisclosed number of Boeing workers volunteered to staybehind and continue work on the projects. These includemaintenance of five Awacs surveillance planes and eighttanker aircraft delivered to the Saudis beginning in 1986,and installation of radar sites for a new computerizedair-defense network known as Peace Shield.</LP><TEXT>   Boeing's goal is to train the Saudis to use the equipment,but a team of contractor representatives is scheduled toremain in the country indefinitely. Boeing wouldn't confirmor deny estimates that as many as 300 of its workers were inthe Persian Gulf area. Unlike other defense contractors,Boeing said it doesn't have any technical representativesdirectly supporting the U.S. military in Operation DesertStorm.   The Boeing workers &quot;didn't come to Saudi Arabia to be in awar,&quot; said Ted Bell, president of the company's Middle Eastoperations, who arrived in Wichita, Kan., the base forBoeing's military aircraft division. He said the workers'decision to stay behind was voluntary, and discounted reportsthat those who declined requests to remain stood to losetheir jobs. He said those who stay will be compensated foradded war stress, but he declined to provide specifics.</TEXT></DOC>